👉 Backtracking – Unique Permutations Using Used Array (LeetCode 47)

Efficiently generate all unique permutations from an array that may contain duplicates.

Perfect when:

You need all arrangements of elements

Order matters

Some elements may repeat

You must avoid duplicate permutations

Classic permutation + backtracking problem

✨ Flashcard

Front:
“How do I generate all unique permutations of an array with duplicates?”

Back:

Sort the array to group duplicates

Track used elements with a used[] array

Pick each unused element

Skip duplicates if the previous identical element wasn’t used

Recurse to build the next position

Undo choice (pop + mark unused)

Stop when all positions are filled → save

⚡ Step-by-Step Combined Explanation

1️⃣ Initialize Result Container
res = []


Stores all unique permutations.

Example:

res = []

2️⃣ Sort Input & Setup Used Array
nums.sort()          # sort to make duplicates adjacent
used = [False] * len(nums)


Sorting ensures duplicates are next to each other → easy to skip.

used[i] tracks if nums[i] is already in the current path.

Example:

nums = [1,1,2]
used = [False, False, False]

3️⃣ Define Backtracking Function
def backtrack(path):
    if len(path) == len(nums):
        res.append(path[:])
        return


path → current permutation being built.

Base case → all positions filled → save a copy.

Mental Map:

[ _, _, _ ]
  ↑ path length

4️⃣ Loop Through All Numbers
for i in range(len(nums)):


Try every number in nums for the current position.

Skip already used numbers:

if used[i]:
    continue


Skip duplicates only if previous duplicate wasn’t used:

if i > 0 and nums[i] == nums[i-1] and not used[i-1]:
    continue


Example:

