👉 Dijkstra – Network Delay Time (LeetCode 743)

Efficiently calculate the minimum time for a signal to reach all nodes in a weighted directed graph.

Perfect when:

You have a weighted graph (edges with travel times)

You want the shortest path from a single source

You need to know when the last node receives the signal

You must handle unreachable nodes

Classic heap-based Dijkstra problem.

✨ Flashcard

Front:
“How do I calculate the network delay time from a source node in a weighted graph?”

Back:

Build adjacency list

Initialize distances to infinity, except source = 0

Use a min-heap (priority queue) to pick the closest node

For each neighbor, update distance if shorter path is found

Push the updated neighbor distance into the heap

Skip outdated distances in the heap

After all nodes processed → check largest distance for the delay

Return -1 if any node is unreachable

⚡ Step-by-Step Combined Explanation
1️⃣ Build Adjacency List
adj = {i: [] for i in range(1, n+1)}
for s, d, w in times:
    adj[s].append((d, w))

adj[node] = list of (neighbor, weight)

Example:

times = [[2,1,1],[2,3,1],[3,4,1]]
adj = {
  1: [],
  2: [(1,1),(3,1)],
  3: [(4,1)],
  4: []
}

Mental Map: “All outgoing roads from each node”

2️⃣ Initialize Distance Table
dist = {i: float("inf") for i in range(1, n+1)}
dist[k] = 0

Distance = shortest known distance from source k

Start with infinity for all nodes → 0 for source

Example:

dist = {1:inf, 2:0, 3:inf, 4:inf}

Mental Map: “How long it will take signal to reach each node”

3️⃣ Setup Min Heap
minHeap = [(0, k)]

Heap contains (distance, node)

Always process the closest node first

Min-heap ensures efficiency

4️⃣ Process Nodes
while minHeap:
    currDist, node = heapq.heappop(minHeap)

Pop the node with smallest distance

currDist = current shortest time to reach this node

5️⃣ Skip Outdated Distances
if currDist > dist[node]:
    continue

Heap may contain old distances for a node

Skip if we already found a shorter path

Example:
Heap = [(3,2),(4,2)]

dist[2] = 3

Pop (4,2) → 4 > 3 → skip

Mental Map: “Ignore slower paths we don’t need”

6️⃣ Explore Neighbors & Update Distances
for nei, weight in adj[node]:
    newDist = currDist + weight
    if newDist < dist[nei]:
        dist[nei] = newDist
        heapq.heappush(minHeap, (newDist, nei))

For each neighbor:

Calculate newDist = distance to current node + edge weight

If newDist is smaller → update dist[nei]

Push (newDist, neighbor) into heap

Mental Map: “Signal spreads along shortest paths → update travel times”

7️⃣ Check Network Delay Time
maxDist = max(dist.values())
return maxDist if maxDist < float("inf") else -1

Largest distance in dist = when the last node receives the signal

If any node still = inf → unreachable → return -1

Example:

dist = {1:0, 2:3, 3:1, 4:4}
max(dist.values()) = 4 → network delay = 4

Mental Map: “Time for the signal to reach all nodes”

🧠 Step-by-Step Dry Run – times = [[2,1,1],[2,3,1],[3,4,1]], n=4, k=2
Step	Heap	Node	dist table	Action
0	[(0,2)]	-	{1:inf,2:0,3:inf,4:inf}	Init
1	[]	2	{1:inf,2:0,3:inf,4:inf}	Explore 2’s neighbors: 1→1,3→1
2	[(1,1),(1,3)]	1	{1:1,2:0,3:1,4:inf}	No neighbors, done
3	[(1,3)]	3	{1:1,2:0,3:1,4:inf}	Explore 3’s neighbor 4→2, push heap
4	[(2,4)]	4	{1:1,2:0,3:1,4:2}	Done
Done	[]	-	{1:1,2:0,3:1,4:2}	max(dist)=2 → return 2
🌳 Heap + Distance Visualization
Heap: [(0,2)]             dist: {1:inf,2:0,3:inf,4:inf}
Pop 2 → neighbors: 1,3
Heap: [(1,1),(1,3)]       dist: {1:1,2:0,3:1,4:inf}
Pop 1 → no neighbors
Pop 3 → neighbor 4
Heap: [(2,4)]             dist: {1:1,2:0,3:1,4:2}
Pop 4 → no neighbors

Network delay = 2 (last node receives signal at t=2)

🔑 Interview Tips

Always use a min-heap for efficiency (O(E log V))

Skip outdated distances (currDist > dist[node])

Network delay = max of all shortest distances

Return -1 if any node unreachable

🧠 One-Line Intuition

“Pick the closest node, spread the signal to neighbors updating shortest times, repeat until all nodes processed → largest distance = network delay.”

👉 Dijkstra on Grid – Swim in Rising Water (LeetCode 778)

Efficiently calculate the minimum time required to reach the bottom-right cell in a grid where water level rises over time.

Perfect when:

You have a grid with elevations

Movement is 4-directional

The “cost” of a path depends on the maximum value along the path

You want the minimum possible maximum

Classic min-heap Dijkstra variation

✨ Flashcard

Front:
“How do I find the minimum time to reach bottom-right in a rising water grid?”

Back:

Treat each cell as a graph node

Time to enter a cell = max(elevation so far, cell elevation)

Use a min-heap to always expand the lowest time cell

Mark visited when popped (finalized)

Stop when bottom-right is popped from heap

⚡ Step-by-Step Combined Explanation
1️⃣ Initialize Grid Info
n = len(grid)
visited = [[False] * n for _ in range(n)]

visited[r][c] → marks finalized cells

Just like dist[] in normal Dijkstra

Mental Map:
“Have we already processed this cell with minimum possible time?”

2️⃣ Setup Min Heap
minHeap = [(grid[0][0], 0, 0)]

Heap contains:

(time_needed, row, col)

Start at (0,0).

Why time = grid[0][0]?

Because water must rise at least to that elevation for you to stand there.

3️⃣ Directions (4 Moves)
directions = [(1, 0), (-1, 0), (0, 1), (0, -1)]

Allowed moves:

Down

Up

Right

Left

Mental Map:
“From each cell, try all four neighbors.”

4️⃣ Process Cells (Dijkstra Loop)
while minHeap:
    time, r, c = heapq.heappop(minHeap)

Pop the cell requiring the smallest time to reach.

Exactly like:

currDist, node = heapq.heappop(minHeap)

in Network Delay Time.

5️⃣ If Destination → Return
if r == n - 1 and c == n - 1:
    return time

Why return immediately?

Because:

Heap guarantees this is the minimum possible time to reach bottom-right.

Once popped → finalized → optimal.

6️⃣ Skip Already Visited
if visited[r][c]:
    continue
visited[r][c] = True

Same as:

if currDist > dist[node]: continue

We mark visited when popped because:

At that moment → we know this is the best possible time for that cell.

Mental Map:
“Lock this cell. We’ve reached it in minimum time.”

7️⃣ Explore Neighbors
for dr, dc in directions:
    nr, nc = r + dr, c + dc

Try all 4 adjacent cells.

Check Valid Move
if 0 <= nr < n and 0 <= nc < n and not visited[nr][nc]:

Ensure:

Inside grid

Not already finalized

8️⃣ Compute Time to Enter Neighbor
newTime = max(time, grid[nr][nc])

This is the KEY difference from normal Dijkstra.

Instead of:

newDist = currDist + weight

We do:

newTime = max(current_path_time, neighbor_elevation)

Why?

Because:

Water must be high enough for all previous cells

AND high enough for this new cell

So we take the larger of the two.

Mental Map:

“Earliest time water must rise so I can stand on this neighbor.”

9️⃣ Push into Heap
heapq.heappush(minHeap, (newTime, nr, nc))

We tell the heap:

“If water rises to newTime, I can reach (nr,nc).”

Heap keeps smallest time first.

🧠 Step-by-Step Dry Run

Example:

grid = [
  [0, 2],
  [1, 3]
]
Step 0

Heap:

[(0,0,0)]
Step 1

Pop (0,0) time=0

Push neighbors:

(1,0) → max(0,1)=1

(0,1) → max(0,2)=2

Heap:

[(1,1,0),(2,0,1)]
Step 2

Pop (1,0) time=1

Push neighbor:

(1,1) → max(1,3)=3

Heap:

[(2,0,1),(3,1,1)]
Step 3

Pop (0,1) time=2

Push:

(1,1) → max(2,3)=3

Heap:

[(3,1,1),(3,1,1)]
Step 4

Pop (1,1) time=3

Destination reached → return 3

🌳 Heap Visualization
Heap: [(0,0,0)]
Pop → explore neighbors
Heap: [(1,1,0),(2,0,1)]
Pop (1,0)
Heap: [(2,0,1),(3,1,1)]
Pop (0,1)
Heap: [(3,1,1),(3,1,1)]
Pop (1,1) → DONE
🔑 Interview Tips

This is Dijkstra where:

distance = maximum elevation along path

Mark visited after popping

Return immediately when reaching bottom-right

Complexity: O(n² log n)

🧠 One-Line Intuition

“Always expand the cell that requires the least water level so far → the first time you reach bottom-right, that water level is the minimum possible.”


👉 Dijkstra – Path with Maximum Probability (LeetCode 1514)

Efficiently calculate the maximum probability path between two nodes in an undirected weighted graph.

Perfect when:

You have a weighted graph

Edge weights represent probabilities

You want the maximum product path

You must handle disconnected graphs

Classic Dijkstra variation (maximize instead of minimize)

✨ Flashcard

Front:
“How do I find the path with maximum probability between two nodes?”

Back:

Build adjacency list (undirected graph)

Initialize probability array with 0

Start node probability = 1

Use a max-heap to always pick the highest probability node

For each neighbor:

newProb = currentProb × edgeProb

Update if larger

Stop when reaching destination

Return 0 if unreachable

⚡ Step-by-Step Combined Explanation
1️⃣ Build Adjacency List (Undirected)
adj = {i: [] for i in range(n)}
for i in range(len(edges)):
    a, b = edges[i]
    prob = succProb[i]
    adj[a].append((b, prob))
    adj[b].append((a, prob))

Mental Map:
“All possible roads with their success probabilities.”

Example:

edges = [[0,1],[1,2],[0,2]]
succProb = [0.5,0.5,0.2]

adj = {
  0: [(1,0.5),(2,0.2)],
  1: [(0,0.5),(2,0.5)],
  2: [(1,0.5),(0,0.2)]
}
2️⃣ Initialize Probability Table
prob = [0.0] * n
prob[start] = 1.0

prob[i] = maximum probability to reach node i

Start node = 1 (100%)

Mental Map:
“Best success chance found so far.”

3️⃣ Setup Max Heap

Python only has min-heap → we store negative probabilities.

import heapq
maxHeap = [(-1.0, start)]

We push (-probability, node)
So the largest probability comes out first.

4️⃣ Process Nodes (Modified Dijkstra)
while maxHeap:
    currProb, node = heapq.heappop(maxHeap)
    currProb = -currProb

Pop the node with the highest probability so far.

5️⃣ Early Stop If Reached Destination
if node == end:
    return currProb

Because heap ensures this is the maximum possible.

6️⃣ Explore Neighbors
for nei, edgeProb in adj[node]:
    newProb = currProb * edgeProb
    if newProb > prob[nei]:
        prob[nei] = newProb
        heapq.heappush(maxHeap, (-newProb, nei))

Key difference from normal Dijkstra:

Instead of:

newDist = currDist + weight

We do:

newProb = currProb * edgeProb

Because probabilities multiply along a path.

Mental Map:

“Probability spreads like signal strength — multiply along edges.”

7️⃣ If No Path Found
return 0.0


🧠 Step-by-Step Dry Run

Example:

n = 3
edges = [[0,1],[1,2],[0,2]]
succProb = [0.5,0.5,0.2]
start = 0, end = 2
Step 0

Heap:

[(-1.0, 0)]
Step 1

Pop (0) prob=1

Push neighbors:

0 → 1 = 1 × 0.5 = 0.5

0 → 2 = 1 × 0.2 = 0.2

Heap:

[(-0.5,1), (-0.2,2)]
Step 2

Pop (1) prob=0.5

Check neighbor 2:

0.5 × 0.5 = 0.25

Better than 0.2 → update.

Heap:

[(-0.25,2), (-0.2,2)]
Step 3

Pop (2) prob=0.25

Reached destination → return 0.25

🔑 Interview Tips

This is Dijkstra but:

Minimize → becomes maximize

Addition → becomes multiplication

Use max-heap (or negative values)

Early stop when reaching end

Return 0 if unreachable

Time Complexity:

O(E log V)
🧠 One-Line Intuition

“Always move through the path with the highest success probability so far — the first time you reach the destination, that probability is the maximum possible.”


👉 Prim’s Algorithm – Minimum Cost to Connect Points (LeetCode 1584)

Efficiently calculate the minimum total cost to connect all points in 2D space using Manhattan distance.

Perfect when:

You have a set of points in 2D

Cost between points = |x1-x2| + |y1-y2|

You want to connect all points with minimum total cost

MST (Minimum Spanning Tree) concept applies

Classic Prim’s algorithm implementation.

✨ Flashcard

Front:
“How do I connect all points with minimum cost?”

Back:

Track visited points (MST nodes)

Keep minDist[i] → cheapest cost to connect point i to MST

Start from any point (here, point 0)

Pick closest unvisited point each step

Add cost and mark as visited

Update remaining points’ minDist with new distances

Repeat until all points are connected

⚡ Step-by-Step Combined Explanation
1️⃣ Initialization
n = len(points)
visited = set()
minDist = [inf]*n
minDist[0] = 0
totalCost = 0

Mental Map:

visited → points included in MST

minDist[i] → cheapest cost to connect point i

minDist[0] = 0 → starting point, cost 0

totalCost → accumulate MST total cost

2️⃣ Pick Closest Unvisited Point
curr = -1
currMin = inf
for i in range(n):
    if i not in visited and minDist[i] < currMin:
        currMin = minDist[i]
        curr = i

Mental Map:

Look at all unvisited points

Pick the one with smallest connection cost to MST

3️⃣ Add Point to MST
visited.add(curr)
totalCost += currMin

Mental Map:

Include this point in MST

Add its connection cost to totalCost

4️⃣ Update Distances of Remaining Points
for i in range(n):
    if i not in visited:
        x1, y1 = points[curr]
        x2, y2 = points[i]
        cost = abs(x1 - x2) + abs(y1 - y2)
        if cost < minDist[i]:
            minDist[i] = cost

Mental Map:

Check if connecting other unvisited points through this new point is cheaper

If yes → update minDist[i]

5️⃣ Repeat Until All Points Are Visited

Loop n times → each iteration adds one point to MST

After all points → totalCost is the answer

6️⃣ Return Result
return totalCost


🔑 Interview Tips

This is Prim’s algorithm for points

Use minDist array instead of heap for simplicity

Manhattan distance → |x1-x2| + |y1-y2|

Complexity: O(n^2)

Works well when n is moderate (~1000)

🧠 One-Line Intuition

“Always add the closest point to the MST so far — total cost grows minimally each step.”

🌳 Dry run
Example Input
points = [[0,0], [2,2], [3,10], [5,2]]

Point 0 → (0,0)

Point 1 → (2,2)

Point 2 → (3,10)

Point 3 → (5,2)

We want minimum total cost to connect all points.

Step 0: Initialization
visited = set()                 # {}
minDist = [0, inf, inf, inf]    # Start from point 0
totalCost = 0
Step 1: Pick node with smallest minDist

Look at minDist = [0, inf, inf, inf]

Smallest unvisited node = 0, cost = 0

Add to MST:

visited = {0}
totalCost = 0 + 0 = 0

Update distances:

Distance 0 → 1: |0-2| + |0-2| = 4 → minDist[1] = 4

Distance 0 → 2: |0-3| + |0-10| = 13 → minDist[2] = 13

Distance 0 → 3: |0-5| + |0-2| = 7 → minDist[3] = 7

Updated minDist: [0, 4, 13, 7]

Step 2: Pick next node with smallest minDist

Smallest unvisited: 1 (cost = 4)

Add to MST:

visited = {0, 1}
totalCost = 0 + 4 = 4

Update distances:

Distance 1 → 2: |2-3| + |2-10| = 9 → minDist[2] = min(13,9) = 9

Distance 1 → 3: |2-5| + |2-2| = 3 → minDist[3] = min(7,3) = 3

Updated minDist: [0, 4, 9, 3]

Step 3: Pick next node with smallest minDist

Smallest unvisited: 3 (cost = 3)

Add to MST:

visited = {0, 1, 3}
totalCost = 4 + 3 = 7

Update distances:

Distance 3 → 2: |5-3| + |2-10| = 10 → minDist[2] = min(9,10) = 9

Updated minDist: [0, 4, 9, 3]

Step 4: Pick next node with smallest minDist

Smallest unvisited: 2 (cost = 9)

Add to MST:

visited = {0, 1, 2, 3}
totalCost = 7 + 9 = 16

All points visited ✅

Step 5: Return Result
return totalCost  # 16

